The course is intended for third year students majoring in Scandinavian languages and cultures. Proficiency in one of the Scandinavian languages at level B1 according to the Common European Framework of Reference is a prerequisite for participating. The course offers a compendious and comparative introduction to the characteristic features of the three Scandinavian languages (Norwegian, Swedish, Danish), as well as presents similarities and differences between the languages from both historical and contemporary perspectives. In that, developments characteristic to these language societies are focused upon. In addition, Icelandic, Faroese and Finland Swedish are discussed together with the overall language situation of the mentioned areas. The focus in language description is on pronunciation, grammar and vocabulary. Besides acquiring basic knowledge, various practical exercises are done. The course consists of lectures, seminars and practical assignments (including presentations). Active participation is expected, there will be a lot of group- and pairwork. There is also a great emphasis on individual work in Moodle.Objectives/eesmärkid:  The purpose of the course is to give an overview of the connections as well as differences between the Scandinavian languages and develops the students' passive language skills in the languages other than their major. In addition, the course prepares students to follow other courses in Scandinavian languages.Learning outcomes/õpiväljund:  After completing the course, the student: - compares and analyses the Scandinavian languages and understands both the connections and differences between them (including lexical ones); - names pronunciation and grammar rules pertaining to languages other than their major; - names the main features of the Nordic language society; - describes the linguistic situation in present day Scandinavia; - is prepared to follow other courses in Scandinavian languages.
